)\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EIgA: \u003C0.1 g/L (0.7-4.0)\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EIgE: \u003C2 kU/L (0-100)\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EB cells: Present\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003ET cells: Present\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Hyper immunoglobulin M syndrome","Immunoglobulin A deficiency","X-linked agammaglobulinaemia","Severe combined immunodeficiency","Common variable immunodeficiency"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient has \u003Cstrong\u003Ehyper immunoglobulin M syndrome\u003C/strong\u003E, characterised by elevated IgM with absent IgG, IgA and IgE. The condition results from defective CD40 ligand expression on T cells, preventing B cells from undergoing immunoglobulin class switching.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EImmunoglobulin A deficiency\u003C/strong\u003E presents with isolated IgA deficiency while other immunoglobulin levels remain normal\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EX-linked agammaglobulinaemia\u003C/strong\u003E shows absence of all immunoglobulins and B cells due to defective early B cell development\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESevere combined immunodeficiency\u003C/strong\u003E affects both T and B cell development, leading to absence of both cell types\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECommon variable immunodeficiency\u003C/strong\u003E typically presents in young adults with low levels of all immunoglobulins\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe presence of B cells with elevated IgM but absent other immunoglobulin classes is pathognomonic for hyper IgM syndrome.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Hyper immunoglobulin M syndrome is characterised by normal or elevated IgM but absent IgG, IgA and IgE due to 